ts including selenium boron and arsenic in november  firstenergy led an aggressive behind the scene attack on ohios electric consumers quietly campaigning to have lawmakers amend state efficiency standards—without public hearings—during the lame duck general assembly sessions energy efficiency became a state mandate in  when lawmakers agreed with former gov ted strickland after months of debate to pass a law requiring electric utilities to help customers use less electricity every year— percent less by  than they did in  under the  law firstenergy slaps companies that do not invest in energy efficiency with higher rates but industries that use their waste heat to make power could escape that rate increase as of november   firstenergy corp has abandoned its behindthescene lobbying campaign to persuade lawmakers to gut a fouryearold law requiring utilities to help customers use less electricity by switching to energy efficient equipment and lighting little blue runedit several cases have been brought against firstenergy for its dumping of coal waste into little blue run lake in west virginia and pennsylvania firstenergy has dumped more than  billion gallons of coal ash and smokestack scrubber waste into the body of water which has contaminated local water supplies with arsenic sulfates sodium calcium magnesium and chloride executivesedit anthony j alexander had been president and chief executive officer of firstenergy from  to  in may  forbes listed alexander as receiving  million in total compensation for the latest fiscal year with a fouryear total compensation of  millioncitation needed notable accidents and incidentsedit the  north american blackout was attributed partly to firstenergys failure to trim the trees around its high voltage lines in a certain sector of ohio heat and extreme power needs caused the lines to sag coming into contact with the trees and causing flashover on friday january   firstenergy acknowledged a coverup of serious safety violations by former workers at the davisbesse nuclear power station and accepted a plea bargain with the us department of justice in lieu of possible federal criminal prosecution the plea bargain relates to the march  discovery of severe corrosion in the pressure vessel of the nuclear reactor contained within the plants containment building in the agreement the company agreed to pay fines of  million with an additional  million to be contributed toward research on alternative energy sources and to habitat for humanity as well as to pay for costs related to the federal investigation in addition two former employees and one former contractor were indicted for purposely deceiving nuclear regulatory commission nrc inspectors in multiple documents including one videotape over several years hiding evidence that the reactor pressure vessel was being seriously corroded by boric acid the maximum penalty for the three is  years in prison the indictment also cites other employees as providing false information to inspectors but does not name them in  the nrc identified two earlier incidents at davisbesse as being among the top five events excluding the actual disaster at three mile island most likely to have resulted in a nuclear disaster in the event of a subsequent failure referencesedit  a b leadership team retrieved  september    a b  k snlcom  retrieved    firstenergy relies heavily on coal for power generation  market realist marketrealistcom retrieved    aaron larson  november  firstenergy wants out of competitive power markets power retrieved  november    a b firstenergy to cut more jobs pittsburgh postgazette november   pp c–   baird k firstenergy transition revving up crains cleveland business serial online april   available from masterfile complete ipswich ma accessed may    baird k  puco orders investigation of firstenergys system crains cleveland business    standard  poors stock guide  north american co v securities and exchange commission  us   findlawcom  weekly corporate gr